<!-- coder-flagship.archml — THE CAPABILITY ENVELOPE, ASSEMBLED AS ONE ORGANISM.

     This specimen exists to answer finding C5 of the agent structural-alignment
     synthesis (doc/research/agents-and-structural-alignment-synthesis.md §1, §6 edit 2):
     the "current flagship agent" that was SCORED there is a union of features spread
     across several living specimens — no single archml had ever paired <m-context>
     (rolling compaction + durable transcript, from coder-service.archml) with <m-jobs>
     (async job registry + parallel sub-agents, from coder-async.archml / coder-team.archml).
     The review's honest relabel was "assemblable today, never yet assembled as one
     specimen." This file assembles it, so the thing that was scored can actually be woken,
     given a real task, and watched.

     The full envelope (agent-loop.md), all as optional components on the one kernel:
       - the tool-calling loop            <m-agent>        (§7)
       - a swappable reasoner             <m-reason>       (§7)
       - the synchronous belt (tools)     terminal + file tools (§8)
       - rolling compaction + persistence <m-context>      (§3, §10)   ← the coder-service half
       - async agency + parallel workers  <m-jobs> + role="subagent" children (§16) ← the coder-async/team half
       - a stall observer                 <m-repeat-guard> (§9)
       - status out                       <m-report>       (§10)
       - a task port (makes it a service) <m-ws>           (§10, §13)
       - the GOVERN seam                  inherent in m-agent (_govern, §6/§11) — a SEAM:
                                          it bubbles a `proposal` event before each tool
                                          call, but with NO <m-norm> wired the call proceeds
                                          unchanged. Left ungoverned on purpose: the synthesis
                                          (C8) credits the ACTIVE machinery, not the seam.

     NOTABLY ABSENT: <m-economy>. The synthesis (C3, factual) found it runs in NO agent —
     its @boundary subscription is mind-shaped (mEconomy.js), so wiring it here would score
     aspiration as reality, the exact error the two reviews caught. Left out on purpose.

     Run it on the LOCAL model (ardincoder-1), seeding the first task via the objective:
       MEDITATOR_MODEL_PROFILE=local-dev \
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE="…a task with independent pieces…" \
         bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/coder-flagship.archml
     It runs the objective as its first task, then — because it has a membrane — idles as a
     SERVICE for the next task rather than retiring, its transcript persisted so a restart
     resumes mid-task. Ctrl-C sleeps the lead and every worker gracefully.

     NOTE (local models): every m-reason call (the lead's AND each worker's) hits the model
     WITH tools, so a local vLLM must be launched with --enable-auto-tool-choice and a
     matching --tool-call-parser (agent-loop.md §12). ardincoder-1 is so configured.

     SHARED WORKSPACE: mindHome resolves per nearest <m-agent>, so nested sub-agents get
     SEPARATE homes by default. For a genuine team building in ONE place, every terminal /
     file-tool / jobs component below carries the SAME explicit root= — the canonical
     shared-workspace attribute — so a file one worker writes is directly visible to the
     others and to the lead. -->
<m-agent name="coder-flagship"
         interlocutor="user"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="80"
         stopWhen="finish-tool">
  You are the LEAD of a small team of coding agents, serving one request at a time inside a
  shared, sandboxed workspace. When given a task, first size it up. When it splits into
  independent pieces that can proceed at the same time, hand each piece to a background
  sub-agent with spawn_agent — then keep working (plan the next piece, prepare the
  integration) while they run. A sub-agent runs one task at a time, so to run two pieces at
  once, give them to two different workers (worker-a and worker-b). For quick checks use the
  plain terminal; for anything SLOW — running a full test suite — spawn it as a background
  job and keep working, then check or wait for it. You will also be told when a background
  job finishes. Never claim something works until you have actually run it and seen it pass.
  Not every request is a coding task — sometimes the user just asks a question; answering it
  fully IS completing the request. Call finish(summary) once the request is genuinely done —
  every sub-agent's result collected and every check seen to pass — and idle until the next.

  <!-- The seed of the WORK — this agent runs it as its first task, then idles as a service.
       Overridable at wake with MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE, exactly as MEDITATOR_ORIGIN seeds a mind. -->
  <m-objective name="objective">
    Split the work into independent pieces, run them in parallel with the workers, then
    integrate and verify the result.
  </m-objective>

  <!-- The lead's own reasoner. Declared FIRST so `reason/reply` (a name-based ref, resolved
       in document order) binds to the lead and not to a worker's identically-named reasoner. -->
  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="3000" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The lead's synchronous belt: read/plan/integrate + quick terminal checks. Heavy,
       slow, or independent work goes to the workers or to a background job. Shared root. -->
  <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="60s" network="off" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-terminal>
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-edit>

  <!-- THE coder-service HALF (agent-loop.md §3, §10). Working memory: mirrors the transcript
       and, when it exceeds `budget`, condenses the oldest turns into a summary (reusing
       m-memory's compressToFit length-loop) while keeping the last `keepRecent` verbatim —
       and persists the transcript to the agent's home, so a restarted service resumes
       mid-task. A pure observer: no change to the kernel. -->
  <m-context name="context" budget="24000" keepRecent="8"></m-context>

  <!-- THE coder-async / coder-team HALF (agent-loop.md §16). Async agency: bubbles
       spawn / check / wait / kill / list_jobs AND spawn_agent(agent, task) — a background
       job that is one of the role="subagent" workers below. Sub-agent jobs and shell jobs
       live in ONE registry, so the same tools collect both. On completion a job NOTIFIES
       via a `nudge` the loop folds into the next turn — the agent learns a job finished
       without polling. Shares the workspace root so a written file is directly runnable. -->
  <m-jobs name="jobs" wall="10m" network="off" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-jobs>

  <!-- The two PARALLEL SUB-AGENTS (agent-loop.md §16). role="subagent" makes each private:
       it does not auto-begin or take tasks over a membrane — it idles until the lead spawns
       it as a job. Each owns its own reasoner and tools (the nearest entity owns its tools),
       all on the SAME shared root, so two pieces genuinely run at once and their files land
       in one workspace. -->
  <m-agent name="worker-a" role="subagent" maxSteps="30" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent on a small team, in a shared sandboxed workspace. Given a concrete,
    self-contained task, carry it out: write code, run it, read what came back, and loop until
    it is genuinely done and checked. Prefer small, verified steps. Never claim something works
    until you have run it and seen it. Call finish(summary) with a short, plain, first-person
    account of what you built or found.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="120s" network="off" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-terminal>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-read-file>
    <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-write-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-edit>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <m-agent name="worker-b" role="subagent" maxSteps="30" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent on a small team, in a shared sandboxed workspace. Given a concrete,
    self-contained task, carry it out: write code, run it, read what came back, and loop until
    it is genuinely done and checked. Prefer small, verified steps. Never claim something works
    until you have run it and seen it. Call finish(summary) with a short, plain, first-person
    account of what you built or found.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="120s" network="off" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-terminal>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-read-file>
    <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-write-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/tmp/claude-1000/-home-sovereign-Meditator/09c6343a-a662-4105-bb12-df35f10f1c7e/scratchpad/flagship-ws"></m-edit>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <!-- Stall guard for the lead itself (agent-loop.md §9): nudge, then halt, a repeated
       action. Each worker carries its own, above. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="8"></m-repeat-guard>

  <!-- Status out (agent-loop.md §10): republishes the agent's status as a `report` topic
       and logs each state change, so a supervisor or the Studio can follow it. -->
  <m-report name="status" every="1"></m-report>

  <!-- Tasks in: the membrane. Under an <m-agent>, m-ws is a TASK PORT — inbound client
       input becomes a `user` turn, and status is broadcast back. Having a membrane also
       makes this a SERVICE: it runs the objective as its first task, then idles for the
       next. Under the Studio the port is assigned automatically (MEDITATOR_WS_PORT). -->
  <m-ws name="ws" port="7644"></m-ws>
</m-agent>
